# WHAT IT IS
#   Port knocking is the practice of keeping a server's firewall
#   closed by default and opening specific ports only when a
#   client sends a magic sequence of TCP/UDP packets to a series
#   of pre-configured "knock" ports (often 4–5 ports in a
#   specific order).  The legacy implementations (knockd,
#   fwknop, dnsknock, the OpenBSD pfctl knock-driver) are
#   notoriously brittle:
#
#     • Sequence knocking is replayable (sniff the knock once,
#       replay it forever)
#     • Stateless implementations leak the knock sequence to
#       any on-path attacker
#     • Most implementations don't authenticate the knock —
#       any party who knows the magic sequence can open the
#       port
#
#   `letmein` solves these problems with a proper challenge-
#   response handshake:  the client sends a "knock" packet
#   announcing the user ID + the resource ID; the server
#   responds with a fresh nonce; the client signs (HMAC-
#   SHA3-512) the nonce + resource ID with the user's shared
#   secret key; the server verifies the HMAC and (if valid)
#   commands the firewall driver to open the requested port
#   or install the requested jump rule.  Replay-protected,
#   authenticated, and stateless on the server side.
#
#   The client side (`letmein`) speaks DNS via the canonical
#   Rust DNS resolver `hickory-resolver` (with full DNS-over-
#   TLS, DNS-over-HTTPS, and DNS-over-QUIC support) to resolve
#   the target server's hostname, configurable via the
#   `--dns` + `--dns-crypt` flags between:
#     • System resolver (whatever /etc/resolv.conf or systemd-
#       resolved or NetworkManager has configured)
#     • Quad9 DoT / DoH endpoint
#     • Google DoT / DoH endpoint
#     • Cloudflare DoT / DoH endpoint
#     • Unencrypted UDP DNS (fallback)
#
#   This makes letmein resilient against on-path DNS hijack
#   attacks that would otherwise be trivial against legacy
#   port-knockers that use unencrypted libc getaddrinfo.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from letmein/src/main.rs
#                       clap-derive `Opts` / `Command` /
#                       `KnockOrRevokeOpts` structs; extracted
#                       via raw.githubusercontent.com fetch of
#                       letmein/src/main.rs)
#
#   letmein [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <COMMAND> [ARGS...]
#
#   Global options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -v, --version                  Show version information and
#                                    exit
#     -c, --config <PATH>            Override the default path to
#                                    the configuration file
#     --verbose                      Show detailed information
#                                    about what happens internally
#     --dns <LIST>                   DNS resolver service (comma-
#                                    separated list of: system,
#                                    quad9, google, cloudflare)
#                                    [default: system,quad9,
#                                              google,cloudflare]
#                                    (`system` is tried first;
#                                    the others are tried in
#                                    listed order if `system`
#                                    fails)
#     --dns-crypt <LIST>             DNS resolver transport
#                                    encryption (comma-separated
#                                    list of: tls, https,
#                                    unencrypted)
#                                    [default: tls,https,
#                                              unencrypted]
#     --seccomp <MODE>               Override the seccomp setting
#                                    from the configuration file
#                                    [values: off, log, kill]
#
#   Commands:
#     knock <HOST> [PORT] [OPTIONS]  Knock a resource on a server
#         -r, --resource <ID>        Resource ID instead of PORT
#                                    (use to knock open a `jump`
#                                    resource)
#         -u, --user <ID>            User ID for authenticating
#                                    the knock request (8-digit
#                                    hex; defaults to [CLIENT]
#                                    default_user from config
#                                    file, or 00000000 if absent)
#         -P, --server-port <PORT>   Override the letmein server
#                                    port (default: from config
#                                    [GENERAL] port, or 5800 if
#                                    absent)
#         -T, --server-port-tcp      Force TCP for the letmein
#                                    server connection
#         -U, --server-port-udp      Force UDP for the letmein
#                                    server connection
#         -4, --ipv4                 Resolve HOST to IPv4 only
#         -6, --ipv6                 Resolve HOST to IPv6 only
#                                    (if both --ipv4 + --ipv6
#                                    are given, knocks on both
#                                    and errors if either fails)
#     revoke <HOST> [PORT] [OPTIONS] Revoke a resource on a
#                                    server (same options as
#                                    knock)
#     gen-key                        Generate a new shared secret
#                                    key (output the typed
#                                    user-id + base64 secret to
#                                    stdout for the operator to
#                                    paste into both client +
#                                    server config files)
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `mbuesch/letmein` declares a **direct** dependency on
#   `hickory-resolver` (with the `system-config`, `tokio`,
#   `tls-ring`, `https-ring`, `quic-ring`, `webpki-roots`,
#   `dnssec-ring` features) in its `letmein/Cargo.toml`
#   (verified via `gh api repos/mbuesch/letmein/contents/
#   letmein/Cargo.toml`).  The `letmein/src/main.rs` source
#   imports the typed primitives via `letmein::resolver::
#   {ResCrypt, ResSrv}` (which themselves wrap
#   `hickory_resolver::*` directly in `letmein/src/
#   resolver/`).
#
#   `hickory-dns/hickory-dns` (formerly `bluejekyll/trust-
#   dns`, renamed in 2024 to align with the Hickory DNS
#   project rebrand) is **THE canonical Rust DNS library** —
#   Benjamin Fry's reference pure-Rust implementation of the
#   DNS protocol stack, in continuous active development
#   since 2015 with 3,800+ ★ on GitHub and 30+ million all-
#   time downloads on crates.io.  It ships as a multi-crate
#   workspace covering every layer of the DNS stack:
#
#     • `hickory-proto`            The typed DNS wire protocol
#                                   parser + serializer
#                                   (RFC 1035 + RFC 3596
#                                   AAAA + RFC 6891 EDNS0 +
#                                   RFC 4033-4035 DNSSEC +
#                                   RFC 7858 DNS-over-TLS +
#                                   RFC 8484 DNS-over-HTTPS +
#                                   RFC 9250 DNS-over-QUIC +
#                                   the full set of typed
#                                   `RecordType::A`, `AAAA`,
#                                   `CAA`, `CNAME`, `DS`,
#                                   `DNSKEY`, `MX`, `NAPTR`,
#                                   `NS`, `NSEC`, `NSEC3`,
#                                   `NULL`, `OPT`, `PTR`,
#                                   `RRSIG`, `SOA`, `SRV`,
#                                   `SSHFP`, `SVCB`, `TLSA`,
#                                   `TXT`, `URI`, `HINFO`,
#                                   `HTTPS`, `KX`, `LOC`,
#                                   `IPSECKEY`, `OPENPGPKEY`,
#                                   `SMIMEA`, `TSIG`, `TKEY`,
#                                   `CSYNC`, `CDNSKEY`,
#                                   `CDS`, `ZONEMD`,
#                                   `ANAME`, `ATMA`,
#                                   `EUI48`, `EUI64`,
#                                   `GPOS`, `HIP`, `ISDN`,
#                                   `KEY`, `MAILA`, `MAILB`,
#                                   `MB`, `MD`, `MF`, `MG`,
#                                   `MINFO`, `MR`, `NID`,
#                                   `L32`, `L64`, `LP`,
#                                   `NIMLOC`, `NSAP`,
#                                   `NSAP_PTR`, `NXT`, `PX`,
#                                   `RP`, `RT`, `SIG`,
#                                   `SINK`, `TA`, `TALINK`,
#                                   `UID`, `UINFO`, `UNSPEC`,
#                                   `WKS`, `X25` named
#                                   record types)
#     • `hickory-resolver`         The typed DNS resolver — the
#                                   client API used by `letmein`
#                                   for hostname-to-address
#                                   resolution.  Exposes the
#                                   typed `Resolver::tokio(...)`
#                                   /  `Resolver::system()`
#                                   typed constructor, the
#                                   typed `resolver.lookup(name,
#                                   record_type)` /
#                                   `lookup_ip(name)` /
#                                   `ipv4_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `ipv6_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `mx_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `srv_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `ns_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `tlsa_lookup(name)` /
#                                   `reverse_lookup(ip)` /
#                                   `txt_lookup(name)` typed
#                                   query methods, the typed
#                                   `NameServerConfigGroup::{
#                                   google(), cloudflare(),
#                                   quad9(), google_tls(),
#                                   cloudflare_tls(), quad9_tls(),
#                                   google_https(), cloudflare_https(),
#                                   quad9_https(), google_h3(),
#                                   cloudflare_h3(), google_quic(),
#                                   cloudflare_quic()}` typed
#                                   provider factories, the
#                                   typed `ProtocolConfig::{
#                                   Udp, Tcp, Tls, Https,
#                                   Quic, H3, Mdns}` typed
#                                   transport-config enum, the
#                                   typed `ResolverOpts` config
#                                   layer with typed `attempts`,
#                                   `cache_size`, `check_names`,
#                                   `edns0`, `negative_max_ttl`,
#                                   `negative_min_ttl`,
#                                   `num_concurrent_reqs`,
#                                   `positive_max_ttl`,
#                                   `positive_min_ttl`,
#                                   `preserve_intermediates`,
#                                   `rotate`,
#                                   `server_ordering_strategy`,
#                                   `try_tcp_on_error`,
#                                   `use_hosts_file`,
#                                   `validate` (DNSSEC),
#                                   `recursion_desired` typed
#                                   fields
#     • `hickory-server`           The typed DNS server-side
#                                   API (authoritative +
#                                   recursive resolver + stub
#                                   resolver + forwarding)
#     • `hickory-recursor`         The typed recursive resolver
#                                   implementation
#     • `hickory-client`           The typed RFC 2136 dynamic-
#                                   DNS update client
#     • `hickory-dns` (the bin)    The reference DNS server
#                                   daemon binary (already in
#                                   corpus as `_hickory-dns`)
#     • `hickory-util` (the bin)   The reference DNS client
#                                   utility binaries (`dns` for
#                                   raw client operations,
#                                   `resolve` for resolver
#                                   queries, `recurse` for
#                                   recursive lookups)
#
#   `hickory-dns/hickory-dns` is the DNS library + server
#   behind essentially every modern Rust DNS deployment:
#
#     • **Cloudflare's Quiche / QUIC implementations** use
#       hickory-proto for DNS over QUIC (RFC 9250)
#     • **Iroh** (the canonical Rust QUIC peer-to-peer
#       networking platform; n0-computer/iroh) uses
#       hickory-resolver for the iroh-relay's DNS layer
#     • **Veloren** (the open-source MMORPG written in Rust)
#       uses hickory-resolver for its client-side
#       name resolution
#     • **Kubeflow Trainer** uses hickory-resolver for the
#       data-cache layer's DNS lookups
#     • **EasyTier** (the open-source mesh-VPN) uses
#       hickory-resolver
#     • **Komodo** (the deployment orchestrator) uses it for
#       the periphery agent's DNS layer
#     • **Oxide Computer's Omicron** (the Oxide rack-scale
#       control plane) uses hickory-resolver in the wicketd
#       provisioning service
#     • **Restate** (the durable execution engine) uses
#       hickory-resolver in its CLI
#     • **RustScan** (the popular Rust port scanner) uses
#       hickory-resolver for target hostname resolution
#     • **Rama** (the Rust web proxy framework) uses it in the
#       rama-cli
#     • **Pingoo** (the Cloudflare-style web edge proxy) uses
#       hickory-resolver
#     • **letmein** (this very project) uses hickory-resolver
#       for client-side hostname-to-address resolution with
#       full DoT / DoH / DoQ encryption
#     • Plus dozens of community DNS over HTTPS / DNS over TLS
#       servers, ad-blocking resolvers, distributed system
#       service-discovery daemons, container runtime DNS
#       layers, mesh VPN coordinator servers, and Cloudflare-
#       style proxy stacks.
#
#   DNS itself (IETF RFC-1035 — Mockapetris 1987) is **the
#   universal name-resolution protocol** that has been the
#   substrate of the entire Internet for ~40 years.  Modern
#   DNS extensions standardized by the IETF include:
#
#     • **EDNS(0)** (RFC 6891) — extension mechanism for
#       larger response payloads + opcode space
#     • **DNSSEC** (RFC 4033/4034/4035 + RFC 5155 NSEC3) —
#       chained-trust authenticated DNS
#     • **DNS-over-TLS / DoT** (RFC 7858) — TLS-encrypted
#       transport on port 853
#     • **DNS-over-HTTPS / DoH** (RFC 8484) — HTTPS-tunneled
#       transport on the `/dns-query` URI template
#     • **DNS-over-QUIC / DoQ** (RFC 9250) — QUIC-encrypted
#       transport on port 853 (ALPN `doq`)
#     • **DNS-over-HTTP/3 / DoH3** (an extension of DoH that
#       uses HTTP/3 transport instead of HTTP/2)
#     • **DDR / Discovery of Designated Resolvers** (RFC 9462)
#       — automatic upgrade from unencrypted resolver to its
#       encrypted equivalent
#     • **SVCB + HTTPS Records** (RFC 9460) — service-binding
#       records that carry typed ALPN + TLS + IPv4/IPv6 hint
#       data in a single DNS lookup
#     • **CAA Records** (RFC 8659) — certificate-authority
#       authorization records for TLS certificate issuance
#     • **TLSA Records** (RFC 6698) — DNS-based authentication
#       of TLS certificate fingerprints (DANE)
#     • **SSHFP Records** (RFC 4255) — DNS-based authentication
#       of SSH host keys
#     • **OPENPGPKEY Records** (RFC 7929) — DNS-published
#       OpenPGP public keys
#     • **SMIMEA Records** (RFC 8162) — DNS-published S/MIME
#       certificates
#
#   The hickory-resolver library covers all of the above.
#
#   Verified via:
#     gh api repos/mbuesch/letmein/contents/letmein/Cargo.toml
#       → [package] name = "letmein"
#       → [package] description = "Authenticated port
